Basic Shiny Apps

author: Mhairi McNeill
date: 24/06/2019

1 Learning Objectives

  • Know how to create a basic Shiny app
  • Understand how to use inputs and outputs to create interactivity.

Duration - 2 hours

2 What are Shiny apps?

Shiny is a way of developing interactive web applications, through writing R code. Generally Shiny apps are used for the interactive exploration of data. Shiny apps can be very basic: for example, just one plot with some interactive element. They can also be very complicated: for example, a large dashboard that lets you visualise complicated data in many ways.

We saw some examples of dashboards back in week 1. Heres another look at the gallery: https://shiny.rstudio.com/gallery/

3 Basic Shiny App

To make a Shiny app, start by opening RStudio. Then go File > New Project > In a new directory > Shiny Web App.

Now we have a Project which is set-up for creating apps. There should be an example app loaded.

Press Run App in the top right of the code panel. This runs the code in front of you and shows you the working app.

You have several options for how to view the app. These can be chosen from the drop down button next to Run App. They are:

  • Window: in another RStudio window
  • Viewer Panel: In the bottom left panel of RStudio
  • External: In a web browser.

For the basic apps well be working on at first, you probably want to view the app in the viewer panel. This means you dont have to leave RStudio. However, later when you make more complicated apps youll probably want to run them in a window or in a browser.

Press the red stop button on the top left of the console to stop the app from running and get your normal R console back.

This app is pretty basic, but we want to go even simpler!

Delete all the code in the app.R file and replace it with this:

library(shiny)

ui <- fluidPage()

server <- function(input, output) {
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

This is just about the most basic Shiny App that its possible to write.

You can see that the app is created using the shinyApp function. This function takes a UI object and a server object. The UI object is defined using fluidPage. Other functions to create a UI are available, but youll be using fluidPage during this course. The server object is just a function with two parameters: input and output.

4 The UI

Were going to build our Shiny App up piece by piece, starting with the UI. Were going to use titlePanel and sidebarLayout to create an app that has a title, a sidebar and a main section.

ui <- fluidPage(

  titlePanel("Title"),

  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      "Sidebar"
    ),

    mainPanel(
      "Main"
    )
  )
)

server <- function(input, output) {

}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

Compare what this app looks like in the viewer pane, compared to running it externally. Since there isnt enough space in the viewer pane, the sidebar layout has been compressed.

The only UI elements in the structure that weve added so far are just plain text. UI elements are separated by commas. Inside sidebarPanel and mainPanel you can extra pieces of text.

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Title"),

  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      "Sidebar 1",
      "Sidebar 2",
      "Sidebar 3"
    ),

    mainPanel(
      "Main 1",
      "Main 2",
      "Main 3"
    )
  )
)

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

Today well be using this sidebar layout for all our Apps. However, be aware that lots of other layouts are available, and can be seen in the Shiny documentation: https://shiny.rstudio.com/articles/layout-guide.html

4.1 Widgets

Now were going to add a widget to our app. Widgets are the basis of the interactivity in our apps; you use the widgets to set values which effect what can be seen in the dashboard.

Lets put a radio button into the sidebar.

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Title"),

  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      radioButtons("season",
        "Summer or Winter Olympics?",
        choices = c("Summer", "Winter")
      ),
    ),

    mainPanel(
      "Main"
    )
  )
)

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

Theres lots of different widgets that you can add to your shiny app. The table below shows them:

Button Description
actionButton Action Button, can be used with reactivity, which we will cover later
checkboxGroupInput A group of check boxes
checkboxInput A single check box
dateInput A calendar to aid date selection
dateRangeInput A pair of calendars for selecting a date range
fileInput A file upload control wizard
helpText Help text that can be added to an input form
numericInput A field to enter numbers
radioButtons A set of radio buttons
selectInput A box with choices to select from
sliderInput A slider bar
submitButton A submit button, similar to an action button
textInput A field to enter text

You can see what each of these widgets looks like here: https://shiny.rstudio.com/gallery/widget-gallery.html

Each widget has its own help file, if you arent sure how to use them. However, they all follow the same pattern for the first few arguments:

Argument Description
inputId Here you give an ID label for your widget. This is how you will refer to widget inside the server code.
label The text that is displayed in the UI next to the widget.
choices For widgets that let you choose between several values, you list the values here.

Task - 10 mins

Add a selectInput widget that lets you chose between the teams United States, Soviet Union, Germany, Italy, Great Britain.

Answer

library(shiny)

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Title"),

  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(

      radioButtons("season",
        "Summer or Winter Olympics?",
        choices = c("Summer", "Winter")
      ),

      selectInput("team",
        "Which Team?",
        choices = c("United States",
                    "Soviet Union",
                    "Germany",
                    "Italy",
                    "Great Britain")
      )
    ),

    mainPanel(
      "Main"
    )
  )
)

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

5 The server

The UI defines how our app looks: the layout, all the static text, where our widgets are, where all our plots and other outputs are.

The server is everything that happens behind the scenes. It defines how we generate all the plots and tables seen by the user. It also defines how the inputs from our widgets affect these plots and tables.

5.1 Creating outputs

You saw earlier that the server is a function that with two parameters: input and output.

For just now well only discuss the output. The output comes from the code in the server. In the server you define elements of a list called output. Each element of this list is of class shiny.render.function, and these special objects are made using the render functions. To make a plot output you use renderPlot, to create text you use renderText and to create a table you use renderTable.

For example lets use the dataset olympics_overall_medals from our course data package. Lets make a simple plot showing the medals won by Britain in the summer Olympics.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(CodeClanData)

olympics_overall_medals %>%
  filter(team == "Great Britain") %>%
  filter(season == "Summer") %>%
ggplot() +
  aes(x = medal, y = count, fill = medal) +
  geom_col()

If we wanted to include this plot in our shiny app, then wed need to

  1. Wrap the code in renderPlot
  2. Assign the value to an output slot
# This is inside the server

output$medal_plot <- renderPlot({

  olympics_overall_medals %>%
    filter(team == "Great Britain") %>%
    filter(season == "Summer") %>%
    ggplot() +
    aes(x = medal, y = count, fill = medal) +
    geom_col()

})

We do all this inside the server function.

And we also need to change the UI. We will specify where in the app this plot is going to go by adding a plotOutput object into the UI.

# This is in the UI

plotOutput("medal_plot")

The name give in plotOutput has to match the output slot we selected in the server.

Each render function has an associated output function:

Render function Output function
renderPlot plotOutput
renderText textOutput
renderTable tableOutput

Putting this all together, and including a new title gives us this app:

library(shiny)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(CodeClanData)

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("British Olympic Medals"),

    sidebarLayout(
      sidebarPanel(

        radioButtons("season",
          "Summer or Winter Olympics?",
          choices = c("Summer", "Winter")
        ),

        selectInput("team",
          "Which Team?",
          choices = c("United States",
                      "Soviet Union",
                      "Germany",
                      "Italy",
                      "Great Britain")
        )
    ),

    mainPanel(
      plotOutput("medal_plot")
    )
  )
)

server <- function(input, output) {
  output$medal_plot <- renderPlot({

    olympics_overall_medals %>%
      filter(team == "Great Britain") %>%
      filter(season == "Summer") %>%
      ggplot() +
      aes(x = medal, y = count, fill = medal) +
      geom_col()
  })
}

  })

Remove this new plot from the the app now. We wont be using it in future.

5.2 Using inputs

The inputs come from widgets. Depending on the action of the user, the inputs will have different values. For example our radio button can have two different values: Summer or Winter. The widgets create a list called input, and each widgets value can be found using the inputId we defined earlier. For example, to get the value of the radio button, and use it in our server then you use input$season.

We can use these values inside the render functions. This will create a plot which changes, depending on the value selected in the widget.

server <- function(input, output) {
  output$medal_plot <- renderPlot({

    olympics_overall_medals %>%
      filter(team == "Great Britain") %>%
      filter(season == input$season) %>%
      ggplot() +
      aes(x = medal, y = count, fill = medal) +
      geom_col()
  })
}

Putting this into our full app gives us:

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("British Olympic Medals"),

    sidebarLayout(
      sidebarPanel(

        radioButtons("season",
          "Summer or Winter Olympics?",
          choices = c("Summer", "Winter")
        ),

        selectInput("team",
          "Which Team?",
          choices = c("United States",
                      "Soviet Union",
                      "Germany",
                      "Italy",
                      "Great Britain")
        )
    ),

    mainPanel(
      plotOutput("medal_plot")
    )
  )
)

server <- function(input, output) {
  output$medal_plot <- renderPlot({

    olympics_overall_medals %>%
      filter(team == "Great Britain") %>%
      filter(season == input$season) %>%
      ggplot() +
      aes(x = medal, y = count, fill = medal) +
      geom_col()
  })
}

shinyApp(ui, server)

6 Code outside the UI and Server

You might have noticed that we placed all the library calls before the UI and server.

Any code here will be run as soon as the app is launched. This makes it easy to write code which can be used by either the UI or the server. For example, here weve found out all the team names first, which lets you chose between any of the teams in the select widget.

library(shiny)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(CodeClanData)

all_teams <- unique(olympics_overall_medals$team)

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Olympic Medals"),

  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      radioButtons("season",
        "Summer or Winter Olympics?",
        choices = c("Summer", "Winter")
      ),

      selectInput("team",
        "Which Team?",
        choices = all_teams,
        selected = "Great Britain"
      )
    ),

    mainPanel(
      plotOutput("medal_plot")
    )
  )
)

server <- function(input, output) {
  output$medal_plot <- renderPlot({
    olympics_overall_medals %>%
      filter(team == input$team) %>%
      filter(season == input$season) %>%
      ggplot() +
      aes(x = medal, y = count, fill = medal) +
      geom_col()
  })
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

You can include code in other files here by using the source function. You may want to include functions that youre using in multiple apps in a separate file. Or you may just want a separate file to help section code better.

We would reccomend writing all your functions in files outside the server.

Task - 5 mins

Change the existing app so that the plot is in a function, which is sourced from a different file.

Answer

# helpers.R

medal_plot <- function(team, season){
  olympics_overall_medals %>%
    filter(team == team) %>%
    filter(season == season) %>%
  ggplot() +
    aes(x = medal, y = count, fill = medal) +
    geom_col()
}
library(shiny)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(CodeClanData)

all_teams <- unique(olympics_overall_medals$team)

# source('helpers.R')

ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Olympic Medals"),

  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      radioButtons("season",
        "Summer or Winter Olympics?",
        choices = c("Summer", "Winter")
      ),

      selectInput("team",
        "Which Team?",
        choices = all_teams,
        selected = "Great Britain"
      )
    ),

    mainPanel(
      plotOutput("medal_plot")
    )
  )
)

server <- function(input, output) {
  output$medal_plot <- renderPlot({
    medal_plot(input$team, input$season)
  })
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

7 Tips

  • Shiny can be tricky! It can be really hard to keep track of what everything does and close all the brackets.
  • Indent everything correctly as you go.
  • Use the warning and error indicators next to the line numbers in RStudio.
  • If the cursor is next to a bracket RStudio will highlight the matching bracket. Check each bracket matches up where you think it should.
  • The error: Error in tag("div", list(...)) : argument is missing, with no default or similar, probably means theres an extra comma somewhere. Its expecting another UI element because of the comma but isnt finding one.
  • You can keep the server in one file (called server.R), and the UI in another (called ui.R). Youll need to put them in one folder, then use shinyAppDir to run the app, rather than shinyApp. Wed reccomend doing this in the project!

8 Recap

  • What functions do you use to define the UI of a Shiny app?
    Answer fluidPage, titlePanel. sidebarLayout, sidebarPanel and mainPanel.
  • What is the general form of a shiny widget?
    Answer <widgit-name>(inputId, label, choices)
  • How to you use a value from a widget in your server?
    Answer With input$<inputId>
  • How do you define an output in the server?
    Answer output$<outputId> <- render*({...})
  • How do you place an output in the UI?
    Answer *output("<outputId>")
